Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46869

This PR is to add graph util C API, which includes:
1. `TF_GrapplerItem` to get preserved/fetched nodes.
2. `TF_GraphProperties` to infer tensor shapes.
3. `TF_FunctionLibraryDefinition` to get OpDef.

This PR is following RFC [Modular TensorFlow Graph C API](https://github.com/tensorflow/community/blob/master/rfcs/20201027-modular-tensorflow-graph-c-api.md).

In profiles from repositry updater runs a huge CPU load originating 
from SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl was found. In parallel excessive runtimes
for project scanning were observed.

Comparing SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl and SimpleFileOwnerQueryImplementation
the latter has an aggressive caching system, which results in much less
cpu usage. Just removing SuiteFileOwnerQueryImpl is not a solution, as
it is used to override the default project detection from
SimpleFileOwnerQueryImplementation.

Explanation from Jaroslav Tulach:

[...] Historically the Graal project provided mx netbeansinit support
which generates 8.2 Ant nbproject/project.xml projects based on content
of suite/mx.suite/suite.py. They were usually located in
suite/src/*/nbproject directories.

To fix this, the idea is, not only to use the current MX project
detection (it requires a folder `mx.proj` to be found in the project
folder `proj`), but also look two level ups from the current directory.
If that directory is recognised as a MX project, that project will
be returned as the project for the requested directory.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/junichi11/netbeans/commits/460042be723b28b430f88c77c1ee7ab18f364892"},{"sha":"5efb6e75212f4885fc76b27ab9e62171b3b317e6","author":{"name":"Jan Lahoda","email":"f0e6c8b88151cef643d02fd650fc0b650ee35a7f@netbeans.org"},"message":"Register JDKPlatformProvider when creating javac in ant's ClassLoader.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/junichi11/netbeans/commits/5efb6e75212f4885fc76b27ab9e62171b3b317e6"},{"sha":"71b0379fd083d726d6a7fd207683dd1d2566d811","author":{"name":"Jan Lahoda","email":"f0e6c8b88151cef643d02fd650fc0b650ee35a7f@netbeans.org"},"message":"Adding test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/junichi11/netbeans/commits/71b0379fd083d726d6a7fd207683dd1d2566d811"},{"sha":"78070a899ea99e1f0d65c7a4db6d9277bfdb1365","author":{"name":"Jaroslav Tulach","email":"872270679d6b683587ccc2f713e451b9fad3065f@oracle.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #2782 from MartinBalin/vscode/build_md_update

3. `TF_FunctionLibraryDefinition` to get OpDef.

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46869

This PR is to add graph util C API, which includes:
1. `TF_GrapplerItem` to get preserved/fetched nodes.
2. `TF_GraphProperties` to infer tensor shapes.
3. `TF_FunctionLibraryDefinition` to get OpDef.

This PR is following RFC [Modular TensorFlow Graph C API](https://github.com/tensorflow/community/blob/master/rfcs/20201027-modular-tensorflow-graph-c-api.md).

Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add missing includes to ensure that we export all the required headers.

These were needed when attempting to use the output folder from the
project generation (with OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis_nn and
TARGET=cortex_m_generic) to build binaries for the SParkfun Edge.

We do not have any CI that would catch such regressions. The issue at
hand is that with large external libraries (such as CMSIS), it can
becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

This issue of managing third_party dependencies is more general that
project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

In fact, in the case of the Sparkfun Edge, the Ambiq SDK packages its
own version of (a small subset of) CMSIS headers. It is possible that
folks might want to consolidate such third party dependencies and
maintain their own version of CMSIS instead of relying on the headers /

Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add missing includes to ensure that we export all the required headers.

These were needed when attempting to use the output folder from the
project generation (with OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis_nn and
TARGET=cortex_m_generic) to build binaries for the SParkfun Edge.

We do not have any CI that would catch such regressions. The issue at
hand is that with large external libraries (such as CMSIS), it can
becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

This issue of managing third_party dependencies is more general that
project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

In fact, in the case of the Sparkfun Edge, the Ambiq SDK packages its
own version of (a small subset of) CMSIS headers. It is possible that
folks might want to consolidate such third party dependencies and
maintain their own version of CMSIS instead of relying on the headers /
sources that are exported by the TFLM project generation scripts.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/WindQAQ/tensorflow/commits/c2611f80f925fda5db47b0e225510821c885a649"},{"sha":"398ecd5381432ba72d2e4c79a656177fc32beb98","author":{"name":"Tamas Bela Feher","email":"6d113d1f7b86c7ce2a423acd09e28148e810f830@nvidia.com"},"message":"TF-TRT CombinedNMS: fix top_k parameter max value","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/WindQAQ/tensorflow/commits/398ecd5381432ba72d2e4c79a656177fc32beb98"},{"sha":"81d3671e01051f7b5a8d1925cb3584512bfafcce","author":{"name":"rsun-bdti","email":"af380e619bdc57e8920c5336db1c5d2df94c6bde@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge branch 'master' into issue-46258-pr4","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/WindQAQ/tensorflow/commits/81d3671e01051f7b5a8d1925cb3584512bfafcce"},{"sha":"8e5d6da9ab9b5de6be37d19099ce156f5102d59e","author":{"name":"rsun","email":"e07b22d99c92b805a489a0254d7957fd2fada7fd@bdti.com"},"message":"Fix micro op expand_dims failure on MacOS CPU test","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/WindQAQ/tensorflow/commits/8e5d6da9ab9b5de6be37d19099ce156f5102d59e"},{"sha":"e2a159ad34a6a775c4a857e56fd5efc26084c086","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge remote-tracking branch 'upstream/master' into project_generation_v2-3","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/WindQAQ/tensorflow/commits/e2a159ad34a6a775c4a857e56fd5efc26084c086"}]

2. `TF_GraphProperties` to infer tensor shapes.
3. `TF_FunctionLibraryDefinition` to get OpDef.

This PR is to add graph util C API, which includes:
1. `TF_GrapplerItem` to get preserved/fetched nodes.
2. `TF_GraphProperties` to infer tensor shapes.
3. `TF_FunctionLibraryDefinition` to get OpDef.

This PR is following RFC [Modular TensorFlow Graph C API](https://github.com/tensorflow/community/blob/master/rfcs/20201027-modular-tensorflow-graph-c-api.md).

This PR is to add graph util C API, which includes:
1. `TF_GrapplerItem` to get preserved/fetched nodes.
2. `TF_GraphProperties` to infer tensor shapes.
3. `TF_FunctionLibraryDefinition` to get OpDef.

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46869

This PR is to add graph util C API, which includes:
1. `TF_GrapplerItem` to get preserved/fetched nodes.
2. `TF_GraphProperties` to infer tensor shapes.
3. `TF_FunctionLibraryDefinition` to get OpDef.

This PR is following RFC [Modular TensorFlow Graph C API](https://github.com/tensorflow/community/blob/master/rfcs/20201027-modular-tensorflow-graph-c-api.md).

project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add missing includes to ensure that we export all the required headers.

These were needed when attempting to use the output folder from the
project generation (with OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis_nn and
TARGET=cortex_m_generic) to build binaries for the SParkfun Edge.

We do not have any CI that would catch such regressions. The issue at
hand is that with large external libraries (such as CMSIS), it can
becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

This issue of managing third_party dependencies is more general that
project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

In fact, in the case of the Sparkfun Edge, the Ambiq SDK packages its
own version of (a small subset of) CMSIS headers. It is possible that
folks might want to consolidate such third party dependencies and
maintain their own version of CMSIS instead of relying on the headers /
sources that are exported by the TFLM project generation scripts.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/c2611f80f925fda5db47b0e225510821c885a649"},{"sha":"398ecd5381432ba72d2e4c79a656177fc32beb98","author":{"name":"Tamas Bela Feher","email":"6d113d1f7b86c7ce2a423acd09e28148e810f830@nvidia.com"},"message":"TF-TRT CombinedNMS: fix top_k parameter max value","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/398ecd5381432ba72d2e4c79a656177fc32beb98"},{"sha":"81d3671e01051f7b5a8d1925cb3584512bfafcce","author":{"name":"rsun-bdti","email":"af380e619bdc57e8920c5336db1c5d2df94c6bde@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge branch 'master' into issue-46258-pr4","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/81d3671e01051f7b5a8d1925cb3584512bfafcce"},{"sha":"8e5d6da9ab9b5de6be37d19099ce156f5102d59e","author":{"name":"rsun","email":"e07b22d99c92b805a489a0254d7957fd2fada7fd@bdti.com"},"message":"Fix micro op expand_dims failure on MacOS CPU test","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/8e5d6da9ab9b5de6be37d19099ce156f5102d59e"},{"sha":"42c39fd0ede5955cb1e9156ada56db7c63819ef1","author":{"name":"Allen Wang","email":"42a4b28f4f152ca57a5f1d251b24aa8bc96b8764@google.com"},"message":"Bring back `ReshardOp`, disable cross replica sharding for mirroed variables.

Specifically,
* Added optional send and recv key to XlaHostCompute similar to _XlaHostComputeMlir
* Make use of optional kXlaOriginalOutsideCompilationNodeName attribute for all ops dealing with outside compilation similar to XlaHostCompute and SendToHost ops. This is required as node names may change in MLIR during export.

Splitting this change specific to old bridge out to keep changes focused only on specific bridges. Testing for the new behavior will be done when we invoke the old bridge from MLIR module.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362547654
Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362547654
Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

[{"sha":"64e374c88b42b7255482f22aa85639ccba5a637e","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Use old bridge in _TpuCompileMlir op unless MLIR bridge was enabled explicitly

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

Change-Id: I0171f8ee41f60bf59ae7ad9019c3a9169de1522e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/107665dd2c0fd087c6bd6f06e63fcf74d1ed2d0f"},{"sha":"31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly delegate learning_rate in LossScaleOptimizer.

This allows LossScaleOptimizer.learning_rate to be accessed and set when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another optimizer wrapper, such as tfa.optimizers.Lookahead.

Normally LossScaleOptimizer finds hyperparameters to delegate by checking the attribute `inner_optimizer._hypers`.  However, the _hyper attribute for wrappers don't have the hyperparameters, so LossScaleOptimizer does not correctly delegate them. Handling this in general is tricky and likely requires adding a new API, which we want to avoid. Instead, we special-case learning_rate by unconditionally delegating it. Other hyperparameters are still not expose when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another wrapper, but in practice usually the only hyperparameter that is accessed on an optimizer is learning_rate, so this is OK.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2403 and https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2332.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362589168
Change-Id: I989771ad505fa9ec85ece05fb7adfdf95f521537","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e"},{"sha":"ca211ae6685c54ecf163070c46ab3b59a8de4d27","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Transform outside compilation ops generated by the new bridge to old bridge semantics

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

This isn't incredibly important, but Kitchen-Terraform is written in and requires tests to be written in Ruby.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/f172585eaa23b9edc40c5b73b066654e1bae7120"},{"sha":"54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: A better error message for custom variable validation

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

within that group.  This means that if you exclude a package that is
in a group, and tell pulp to copy over the group the package that is
excluded will get copied.  This is a behavior change from pulp2.
To handle this, we need to treat groups like errata, where by you need

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46869

project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

[{"sha":"9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0","author":{"name":"Waqar Hameed","email":"1b4ea0cc3b7e92e1b63958403a4b855ff79112a7@gmail.com"},"message":"lite: nnapi: Check memory mapping errors after NNMemory()

There are no error checks in the constructor `NNMemory::NNMemory()`.
When creating a shared memory fd, `NNMemory::fd_` could be set to a
negative value due to errors. Thus, when trying to `mmap` this,
`NNMemory::data_ptr_` will be set to `MAP_FAILED` (and which in turn
will yield an invalid call to `ANeuralNetworksMemory_createFromFd()`) in
the constructor.

Ideally, one should check for errors early. However, since Google's C++
style guide prohibits the use of exceptions, we need to check this
explicitly after the constructor instead. We check `NNMemory::data_ptr_`
for any errors (since `NNMemory::fd_` is private).

Signed-off-by: Waqar Hameed <whame91@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/whame/tensorflow/commits/9f5e38b536e0cfa239e53fb57bf6789d7a5f9ad0"}]

Some resource ops such as AssignAddVariable are decomposed into multiple ops and the device assigment is lost. Ops with explicit device assigmnment are now wrapped in a launch op with the same device attribute.  When the op is decomposed it is within the LaunchOp.  The ops are later hoisted in the LaunchToDeviceAttributePass and the device attribute written for each decomposed op.

[{"sha":"f4515dd5de7e19cab2b5d5ec0b9cc63acbd00c3f","author":{"name":"Ken Franko","email":"99675e19a4e19629720cc97f93d3a35dad14ac72@google.com"},"message":"Add DeviceAttributeToLaunchOp pass before DecomposeResourceOps pass.

Some resource ops such as AssignAddVariable are decomposed into multiple ops and the device assigment is lost. Ops with explicit device assigmnment are now wrapped in a launch op with the same device attribute.  When the op is decomposed it is within the LaunchOp.  The ops are later hoisted in the LaunchToDeviceAttributePass and the device attribute written for each decomposed op.

Some resource ops such as AssignAddVariable are decomposed into multiple ops and the device assigment is lost. Ops with explicit device assigmnment are now wrapped in a launch op with the same device attribute.  When the op is decomposed it is within the LaunchOp.  The ops are later hoisted in the LaunchToDeviceAttributePass and the device attribute written for each decomposed op.

  operations upfront helps avoid creating invalid MLIR, as well as can enable other
  optimizations.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362547654
Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Some resource ops such as AssignAddVariable are decomposed into multiple ops and the device assigment is lost. Ops with explicit device assigmnment are now wrapped in a launch op with the same device attribute.  When the op is decomposed it is within the LaunchOp.  The ops are later hoisted in the LaunchToDeviceAttributePass and the device attribute written for each decomposed op.

[{"sha":"31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly delegate learning_rate in LossScaleOptimizer.

This allows LossScaleOptimizer.learning_rate to be accessed and set when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another optimizer wrapper, such as tfa.optimizers.Lookahead.

Normally LossScaleOptimizer finds hyperparameters to delegate by checking the attribute `inner_optimizer._hypers`.  However, the _hyper attribute for wrappers don't have the hyperparameters, so LossScaleOptimizer does not correctly delegate them. Handling this in general is tricky and likely requires adding a new API, which we want to avoid. Instead, we special-case learning_rate by unconditionally delegating it. Other hyperparameters are still not expose when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another wrapper, but in practice usually the only hyperparameter that is accessed on an optimizer is learning_rate, so this is OK.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2403 and https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2332.

[{"sha":"ca211ae6685c54ecf163070c46ab3b59a8de4d27","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Transform outside compilation ops generated by the new bridge to old bridge semantics

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

[{"sha":"0b45981fc6525c0b677bb019566fcf12445142f2","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Generalize tf-rewrite-tpu-embedding-ops pass to handle embedding ops within regions

Currently, the pass assumes embedding ops to be directly in a function and was working only because functional control flow to regions pass introduces call functions so the embedding ops ended up being in a separate function.

The above won't be true for this pass's usage to rewrite these ops in MLIR module before converting it to Graph for compilation using the old bridge second phase.

These were needed when attempting to use the output folder from the
project generation (with OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis_nn and
TARGET=cortex_m_generic) to build binaries for the SParkfun Edge.

We do not have any CI that would catch such regressions. The issue at
hand is that with large external libraries (such as CMSIS), it can
becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

This issue of managing third_party dependencies is more general that
project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

In fact, in the case of the Sparkfun Edge, the Ambiq SDK packages its
own version of (a small subset of) CMSIS headers. It is possible that
folks might want to consolidate such third party dependencies and
maintain their own version of CMSIS instead of relying on the headers /

[{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

  operations upfront helps avoid creating invalid MLIR, as well as can enable other
  optimizations.

Change-Id: I0171f8ee41f60bf59ae7ad9019c3a9169de1522e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/107665dd2c0fd087c6bd6f06e63fcf74d1ed2d0f"},{"sha":"31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly delegate learning_rate in LossScaleOptimizer.

This allows LossScaleOptimizer.learning_rate to be accessed and set when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another optimizer wrapper, such as tfa.optimizers.Lookahead.

Normally LossScaleOptimizer finds hyperparameters to delegate by checking the attribute `inner_optimizer._hypers`.  However, the _hyper attribute for wrappers don't have the hyperparameters, so LossScaleOptimizer does not correctly delegate them. Handling this in general is tricky and likely requires adding a new API, which we want to avoid. Instead, we special-case learning_rate by unconditionally delegating it. Other hyperparameters are still not expose when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another wrapper, but in practice usually the only hyperparameter that is accessed on an optimizer is learning_rate, so this is OK.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2403 and https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2332.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362589168
Change-Id: I989771ad505fa9ec85ece05fb7adfdf95f521537","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e"},{"sha":"ca211ae6685c54ecf163070c46ab3b59a8de4d27","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Transform outside compilation ops generated by the new bridge to old bridge semantics

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

Change-Id: I6d617b36f210f205ac73f5168674b2675f7c9ca9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/0476d2d1c8d8d9e4ad66f4a3b71cfd837b22426d"},{"sha":"64e374c88b42b7255482f22aa85639ccba5a637e","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Use old bridge in _TpuCompileMlir op unless MLIR bridge was enabled explicitly

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

Some resource ops such as AssignAddVariable are decomposed into multiple ops and the device assigment is lost. Ops with explicit device assigmnment are now wrapped in a launch op with the same device attribute.  When the op is decomposed it is within the LaunchOp.  The ops are later hoisted in the LaunchToDeviceAttributePass and the device attribute written for each decomposed op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362547654
Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362588165
Change-Id: I0171f8ee41f60bf59ae7ad9019c3a9169de1522e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KaycoinsInc/tensorflow/commits/107665dd2c0fd087c6bd6f06e63fcf74d1ed2d0f"},{"sha":"31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly delegate learning_rate in LossScaleOptimizer.

This allows LossScaleOptimizer.learning_rate to be accessed and set when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another optimizer wrapper, such as tfa.optimizers.Lookahead.

Normally LossScaleOptimizer finds hyperparameters to delegate by checking the attribute `inner_optimizer._hypers`.  However, the _hyper attribute for wrappers don't have the hyperparameters, so LossScaleOptimizer does not correctly delegate them. Handling this in general is tricky and likely requires adding a new API, which we want to avoid. Instead, we special-case learning_rate by unconditionally delegating it. Other hyperparameters are still not expose when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another wrapper, but in practice usually the only hyperparameter that is accessed on an optimizer is learning_rate, so this is OK.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2403 and https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2332.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362589168
Change-Id: I989771ad505fa9ec85ece05fb7adfdf95f521537","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KaycoinsInc/tensorflow/commits/31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e"},{"sha":"ca211ae6685c54ecf163070c46ab3b59a8de4d27","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Transform outside compilation ops generated by the new bridge to old bridge semantics

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362599513
Change-Id: I6d617b36f210f205ac73f5168674b2675f7c9ca9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KaycoinsInc/tensorflow/commits/0476d2d1c8d8d9e4ad66f4a3b71cfd837b22426d"},{"sha":"64e374c88b42b7255482f22aa85639ccba5a637e","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Use old bridge in _TpuCompileMlir op unless MLIR bridge was enabled explicitly

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

Change-Id: Ie44b53d3eff2a19ea76f643ffd977997ce69d217","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/5097e6b36350f16032db950792c54f50a5385ec9"},{"sha":"0b45981fc6525c0b677bb019566fcf12445142f2","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Generalize tf-rewrite-tpu-embedding-ops pass to handle embedding ops within regions

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362588165
Change-Id: I0171f8ee41f60bf59ae7ad9019c3a9169de1522e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/107665dd2c0fd087c6bd6f06e63fcf74d1ed2d0f"},{"sha":"31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly delegate learning_rate in LossScaleOptimizer.

This allows LossScaleOptimizer.learning_rate to be accessed and set when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another optimizer wrapper, such as tfa.optimizers.Lookahead.

Normally LossScaleOptimizer finds hyperparameters to delegate by checking the attribute `inner_optimizer._hypers`.  However, the _hyper attribute for wrappers don't have the hyperparameters, so LossScaleOptimizer does not correctly delegate them. Handling this in general is tricky and likely requires adding a new API, which we want to avoid. Instead, we special-case learning_rate by unconditionally delegating it. Other hyperparameters are still not expose when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another wrapper, but in practice usually the only hyperparameter that is accessed on an optimizer is learning_rate, so this is OK.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2403 and https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2332.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362589168
Change-Id: I989771ad505fa9ec85ece05fb7adfdf95f521537","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e"},{"sha":"ca211ae6685c54ecf163070c46ab3b59a8de4d27","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Transform outside compilation ops generated by the new bridge to old bridge semantics

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362599513
Change-Id: I6d617b36f210f205ac73f5168674b2675f7c9ca9","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/0476d2d1c8d8d9e4ad66f4a3b71cfd837b22426d"},{"sha":"64e374c88b42b7255482f22aa85639ccba5a637e","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Use old bridge in _TpuCompileMlir op unless MLIR bridge was enabled explicitly

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362588165
Change-Id: I0171f8ee41f60bf59ae7ad9019c3a9169de1522e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/107665dd2c0fd087c6bd6f06e63fcf74d1ed2d0f"},{"sha":"31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly delegate learning_rate in LossScaleOptimizer.

This allows LossScaleOptimizer.learning_rate to be accessed and set when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another optimizer wrapper, such as tfa.optimizers.Lookahead.

Normally LossScaleOptimizer finds hyperparameters to delegate by checking the attribute `inner_optimizer._hypers`.  However, the _hyper attribute for wrappers don't have the hyperparameters, so LossScaleOptimizer does not correctly delegate them. Handling this in general is tricky and likely requires adding a new API, which we want to avoid. Instead, we special-case learning_rate by unconditionally delegating it. Other hyperparameters are still not expose when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another wrapper, but in practice usually the only hyperparameter that is accessed on an optimizer is learning_rate, so this is OK.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2403 and https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2332.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362589168
Change-Id: I989771ad505fa9ec85ece05fb7adfdf95f521537","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e"},{"sha":"ca211ae6685c54ecf163070c46ab3b59a8de4d27","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Transform outside compilation ops generated by the new bridge to old bridge semantics

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

This allows LossScaleOptimizer.learning_rate to be accessed and set when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another optimizer wrapper, such as tfa.optimizers.Lookahead.

Normally LossScaleOptimizer finds hyperparameters to delegate by checking the attribute `inner_optimizer._hypers`.  However, the _hyper attribute for wrappers don't have the hyperparameters, so LossScaleOptimizer does not correctly delegate them. Handling this in general is tricky and likely requires adding a new API, which we want to avoid. Instead, we special-case learning_rate by unconditionally delegating it. Other hyperparameters are still not expose when LossScaleOptimizer wraps another wrapper, but in practice usually the only hyperparameter that is accessed on an optimizer is learning_rate, so this is OK.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2403 and https://github.com/tensorflow/addons/issues/2332.

Change-Id: I989771ad505fa9ec85ece05fb7adfdf95f521537","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/31d58c65625592453cb9456e9cf663d891de599e"},{"sha":"ca211ae6685c54ecf163070c46ab3b59a8de4d27","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Transform outside compilation ops generated by the new bridge to old bridge semantics

Old bridge,
* Uses XlaHostCompute op instead of _XlaHostComputeMlir op.
* Requires SendToHost and RecvFromHost ops to have _dtoh_0 and _htod_0 suffixes.
* Predecessor communication ops are set explicitly to add appropriate control dependencies in the HLO. Old bridge compiles one op at a time and doesn't have ordering information can't be derived from the list of graph nodes. Therefore, it sets original node names and token input node names to add control dependencies using tokens.

This pass will be used to transform MLIR module generated by the MLIR bridge and then exporting it to TensorFlow Graph to compile it using the old bridge.

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

the input should result in empty collections in the output.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/178a9b32d7eee889e12d402ec066edbcdc0d96b6"},{"sha":"66f8d1c1c28bf729bd1b2b3919377ed9291f6080","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"functions: Fix defaults mismatched types fallback

We allow primitive fallback values which have mismatched types, but only
if there is a conversion to the target type. Previously we would allow
unsafe conversions (e.g. string to bool), but later had no capacity to
return an error if the conversion failed due to the value of the

Fixes #27506

Add a new flag `-lockfile=readonly` to `terraform init`.
It would be useful to allow us to suppress dependency lockfile changes
explicitly.

The type of the `-lockfile` flag is string rather than bool, leaving
room for future extensions to other behavior variants.

The readonly mode suppresses lockfile changes, but should verify
checksums against the information already recorded. It should conflict
with the `-upgrade` flag.

Note: In the original use-case described in #27506, I would like to
suppress adding zh hashes, but a test code here suppresses adding h1
hashes because it's easy for testing.

This allows incremental rollout of the bridge.

Old bridge is invoked by,
* Deserializing MLIR
* Using mhlo.is_same_data_across_replicas arg attributes in the main function to update metadata
* Exporting the MLIR module to a temporary function library after running a pass pipeline
* Compiling the function using the old bridge code path

If the conversion to graph or compilation using the old bridge fails, then compilation is aborted instead of trying out the MLIR bridge. This makes the expectations clearer. One possibility could be to evolve this similar to first phase of the bridge.

3. `TF_FunctionLibraryDefinition` to get OpDef.

These were needed when attempting to use the output folder from the
project generation (with OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis_nn and
TARGET=cortex_m_generic) to build binaries for the SParkfun Edge.

We do not have any CI that would catch such regressions. The issue at
hand is that with large external libraries (such as CMSIS), it can
becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

This issue of managing third_party dependencies is more general that
project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

In fact, in the case of the Sparkfun Edge, the Ambiq SDK packages its
own version of (a small subset of) CMSIS headers. It is possible that
folks might want to consolidate such third party dependencies and
maintain their own version of CMSIS instead of relying on the headers /

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46869

This PR is to add graph util C API, which includes:
1. `TF_GrapplerItem` to get preserved/fetched nodes.
2. `TF_GraphProperties` to infer tensor shapes.
3. `TF_FunctionLibraryDefinition` to get OpDef.

This PR is following RFC [Modular TensorFlow Graph C API](https://github.com/tensorflow/community/blob/master/rfcs/20201027-modular-tensorflow-graph-c-api.md).

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46869

This PR is to add graph util C API, which includes:
1. `TF_GrapplerItem` to get preserved/fetched nodes.
2. `TF_GraphProperties` to infer tensor shapes.
3. `TF_FunctionLibraryDefinition` to get OpDef.

This PR is following RFC [Modular TensorFlow Graph C API](https://github.com/tensorflow/community/blob/master/rfcs/20201027-modular-tensorflow-graph-c-api.md).

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46869

This PR is to add graph util C API, which includes:
1. `TF_GrapplerItem` to get preserved/fetched nodes.
2. `TF_GraphProperties` to infer tensor shapes.
3. `TF_FunctionLibraryDefinition` to get OpDef.

This PR is following RFC [Modular TensorFlow Graph C API](https://github.com/tensorflow/community/blob/master/rfcs/20201027-modular-tensorflow-graph-c-api.md).

* Change Xtensa softmax kernel to only support int8->int16.

Size reduction of ~4KB:

```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=F1_190305_swupgrade keyword_benchmark -j8 BUILD_TYPE=release
xt-size tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/xtensa_fusion_f1_release/bin/keyword_benchmark
```

Without this change:
```
   text	   data	    bss	    dec	    hex	filename
  88712	    384	  22704	 111800	  1b4b8
  tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/xtensa_fusion_f1_release/bin/keyword_benchmark
```

With this change:
```
   text	   data	    bss	    dec	    hex	filename
  84496	    384	  22704	 107584	  1a440	tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/gen/xtensa_fusion_f1_release/bin/keyword_benchmark
```

For all of the Xtensa kernels, we are currently limiting support to only
what we need for the keyword_benchmark. While this is not a scalable
solution (and the reason why we have the selective registration of
kernel variants), we are currently keeping the Fusion F1 and Hifimini
implementations consistently narrow in scope.

This ensures:
 * we have a smaller memory footprint (arguably overfitting to a
   particular use-case)
 * all the code has correspinding unit tests (any float test cases are
   currently disabled for Xtensa with #if !defined(XTENSA))
 * The current size of the keyword_benchmark binary serves as a baseline
   to make sure that the selective registration API works as expected.

* [XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

This issue of managing third_party dependencies is more general that
project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

folks might want to consolidate such third party dependencies and
maintain their own version of CMSIS instead of relying on the headers /

serialization when possible and instead it's like a live tree being
built.

This is not wired up. I just need something for the flow types since
Flight and Fizz are both handled by the isServerSupported flag.

[{"sha":"c2611f80f925fda5db47b0e225510821c885a649","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add missing includes to ensure that we export all the required headers.

These were needed when attempting to use the output folder from the
project generation (with OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis_nn and
TARGET=cortex_m_generic) to build binaries for the SParkfun Edge.

We do not have any CI that would catch such regressions. The issue at
hand is that with large external libraries (such as CMSIS), it can
becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

This issue of managing third_party dependencies is more general that
project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

In fact, in the case of the Sparkfun Edge, the Ambiq SDK packages its
own version of (a small subset of) CMSIS headers. It is possible that
folks might want to consolidate such third party dependencies and
maintain their own version of CMSIS instead of relying on the headers /
sources that are exported by the TFLM project generation scripts.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/c2611f80f925fda5db47b0e225510821c885a649"},{"sha":"e2a159ad34a6a775c4a857e56fd5efc26084c086","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge remote-tracking branch 'upstream/master' into project_generation_v2-3","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/e2a159ad34a6a775c4a857e56fd5efc26084c086"},{"sha":"e45edc493dda55a60ced65315ca6360da3812ef4","author":{"name":"Raman Sarokin","email":"801f4ea5fa3def449b856907ab66b1f4ecb92c87@google.com"},"message":"Added tests for Split channels(Metal and OpenCL).

Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

This commit adds a comprehensive JSON format for diagnostics, which
ensures that all current diagnostic output can be semantically
represented in a machine-readable format. The diagnostic formatter
interface remains unchanged, but it first transforms its input via the
JSON format to ensure that there is only one code path for creating the
diagnostic data.

The JSON diagnostic renderer extracts the non-presentational logic from
the format package, and returns a structure which can either be
marshaled into JSON or rendered as text. The resulting text diagnostic
output is unchanged for all cases covered by unit tests and my own
manual testing.

Included in this commit are a number of golden reference files for the
marshaled JSON output of a diagnostic. This format should change rarely
if at all, and these are in place to ensure that any changes to the
format are intentional and considered.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d9d88b92439b9047570bcfa5fc1e90cf71aec60d"},{"sha":"c92826c14de925b167ee40efb6bc31fe85d03007","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Use standard JSON diagnostics for validate

Now that we have a comprehensive JSON diagnostic structure, we can use
it in the `validate -json` output instead of the inline version. Note
that this changes the output of `validate -json` in two ways:

1. We fix some off-by-one errors caused by zero-width highlight ranges.
   This aligns the JSON diagnostic output with the text output seen by
   most Terraform users, so I consider this a bug fix.
2. We add the `snippet` field to the JSON diagnostics where available.
   This is purely additive and is permitted under our JSON format
   stability guarantees.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/c92826c14de925b167ee40efb6bc31fe85d03007"},{"sha":"2a85f0483fb6d17e4c54bde60bbd7f03028b6161","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@hashicorp.com"},"message":"website: Update validate -json diags documentation

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362547654
Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Change-Id: I08e98c3d3a211e8522e42d9ae600b44819b797db","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/albertvillanova/tensorflow/commits/6130226a8c1b8787adf4c49bdb0fff5292bd861c"},{"sha":"53ff2339b3c05a6efbe5bdbdd6c40b8973fb8e17","author":{"name":"Jose Baiocchi","email":"2c5064b37befcda621d52370dff81833faf858cd@google.com"},"message":"TensorBoard callback: handle exceptions due to concurrent profiling

In addition to handling exceptions, try to prevent callbacks from interfering with other clients (including other callbacks) by ensuring a callback only calls profiler.stop() if it successfully called profiler.start().

These were needed when attempting to use the output folder from the
project generation (with OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis_nn and
TARGET=cortex_m_generic) to build binaries for the SParkfun Edge.

We do not have any CI that would catch such regressions. The issue at
hand is that with large external libraries (such as CMSIS), it can
becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

This issue of managing third_party dependencies is more general that
project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

In fact, in the case of the Sparkfun Edge, the Ambiq SDK packages its
own version of (a small subset of) CMSIS headers. It is possible that
folks might want to consolidate such third party dependencies and
maintain their own version of CMSIS instead of relying on the headers /

Specifically,
* Added optional send and recv key to XlaHostCompute similar to _XlaHostComputeMlir
* Make use of optional kXlaOriginalOutsideCompilationNodeName attribute for all ops dealing with outside compilation similar to XlaHostCompute and SendToHost ops. This is required as node names may change in MLIR during export.

Splitting this change specific to old bridge out to keep changes focused only on specific bridges. Testing for the new behavior will be done when we invoke the old bridge from MLIR module.

Change-Id: I6ddb428c549fa46b84807c3933444d7bd8ed9518","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/883c547bbc020ed2f89beedfa9dca52bc45da3d5"},{"sha":"f4515dd5de7e19cab2b5d5ec0b9cc63acbd00c3f","author":{"name":"Ken Franko","email":"99675e19a4e19629720cc97f93d3a35dad14ac72@google.com"},"message":"Add DeviceAttributeToLaunchOp pass before DecomposeResourceOps pass.

Some resource ops such as AssignAddVariable are decomposed into multiple ops and the device assigment is lost. Ops with explicit device assigmnment are now wrapped in a launch op with the same device attribute.  When the op is decomposed it is within the LaunchOp.  The ops are later hoisted in the LaunchToDeviceAttributePass and the device attribute written for each decomposed op.

Change-Id: Id03d375b6a54333b30bff9ff214614df6043d96e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/f4515dd5de7e19cab2b5d5ec0b9cc63acbd00c3f"},{"sha":"17e2235355ea780504eecf5cfe52f58db66ac968","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Add simplification for real/imag with non-complex inputs.

  operations upfront helps avoid creating invalid MLIR, as well as can enable other
  optimizations.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362547654
Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Change-Id: I6ddb428c549fa46b84807c3933444d7bd8ed9518","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/883c547bbc020ed2f89beedfa9dca52bc45da3d5"},{"sha":"f4515dd5de7e19cab2b5d5ec0b9cc63acbd00c3f","author":{"name":"Ken Franko","email":"99675e19a4e19629720cc97f93d3a35dad14ac72@google.com"},"message":"Add DeviceAttributeToLaunchOp pass before DecomposeResourceOps pass.

Some resource ops such as AssignAddVariable are decomposed into multiple ops and the device assigment is lost. Ops with explicit device assigmnment are now wrapped in a launch op with the same device attribute.  When the op is decomposed it is within the LaunchOp.  The ops are later hoisted in the LaunchToDeviceAttributePass and the device attribute written for each decomposed op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362547654
Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362547654
Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Some resource ops such as AssignAddVariable are decomposed into multiple ops and the device assigment is lost. Ops with explicit device assigmnment are now wrapped in a launch op with the same device attribute.  When the op is decomposed it is within the LaunchOp.  The ops are later hoisted in the LaunchToDeviceAttributePass and the device attribute written for each decomposed op.

Change-Id: Id03d375b6a54333b30bff9ff214614df6043d96e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/f4515dd5de7e19cab2b5d5ec0b9cc63acbd00c3f"},{"sha":"17e2235355ea780504eecf5cfe52f58db66ac968","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Add simplification for real/imag with non-complex inputs.

  optimizations.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 362547654
Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.

Some resource ops such as AssignAddVariable are decomposed into multiple ops and the device assigment is lost. Ops with explicit device assigmnment are now wrapped in a launch op with the same device attribute.  When the op is decomposed it is within the LaunchOp. PiperOrigin-RevId: 362547654
Change-Id: If016f365b43b087f48dcc82bd1be10af08e70c99","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/641fd16f964e322657571c3b7f5babc1bde6626c"},{"sha":"a441f318859964b90f6aff4e7d0dc7c6c039d3c4","author":{"name":"Rahul Joshi","email":"15277936ae82919baaa227d3a37b5e73c80bf8d2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Introduce NCCL based collective permute.

- Add NCCL based collective permute which can work both cross replica (single host)
  as well as cross partition (multiple hosts).
- For a single group of all the replicas/partitions in the execution, irrespective of whether
  the actually need to issue an NCCL API calls, so that replica/partition #x is assigned
  NCCL rank k.
- Maintain a map to map each id to a source/target pair which indicate the rank from
  which to receive data and the rank to which send data.
- Continue to use the existing CollectivePermuteThunk for single partition cross replica
  permute.
- Note that this requires the use of NCCL_LAUNCH_MODE=PARALLEL to avoid some
  issues with NCCL 2.8.x related to non-uniform data size among ranks when using
  point-to-point communication primitives.
